        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
            "PrimaryAttribute": "QID1219691457",
            "SecondaryAttribute": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation. As part of a group project, your team has t...",
            "TertiaryAttribute": null,
            "Payload": {
                "QuestionText": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team has to submit a 200-word news article and\nyour teammate, Brandon, is in charge of writing it. To do so, he used the newest\nLLM, designed to have a very human-like writing style.\n<br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor actively tracks new\ndevelopments in LLMs and has already cautioned against their use in coursework.\nYou are worried he will suspect the article was produced with the help of an\nLLM, which would penalize the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is therefore to edit the text so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this new LLM, you first generate\ntwo sample articles using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Example 1</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Russia's society: Why so many oligarchs?</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>The rise of Russia\u2019s oligarchs is rooted in the transition from a state-controlled economy to capitalism which occurred in the early 1990s. When the Soviet Union collapsed this resulted in the loss of a vast amount of country assets ranging from industries such as oil and gas to media companies that were privatized. In theory privatization was meant to distribute ownership among all citizens in a more fair manner. However, this practice produced a small group of well connected businessmen who acquired major enterprises at a small price.</p>\n           <p>A key moment during this transition was the \u201cloans for shares\u201d program of the mid 1990s when the government auctioned stakes in large companies in exchange for short term loans while attempting to manage the fiscal crisis. Political insiders with connections often won these auctions which consolidated control over the lucrative industries responsible for controlling Russia's natural resources. In addition, weak regulatory institutions and an underdeveloped legal system allowed wealth to grow.</p>\n           <p>Russia\u2019s economy, which was already heavily dependent on items such as oil, gas, and metals further grew fortunes as global prices rose in the 2000s. Close ties between business leaders and political power structures became a defining feature of the Russian system.</p>\n           <p>Over the following decades the state reclaimed control over these key sectors which helped to reshape the balance between private wealth and government. authority. Nevertheless, the legacy of privatization remains a staple of the period after the fall of the Soviet Union. Thus, the concentration of assets in a handful of powerful figures in Russia remains a defining characteristic of Russia\u2019s post Soviet economic landscape.</p></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Example 2</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Why are companies moving to the cloud? 81% simply fear 'missing out'</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>An increasing number of companies have been migrating to cloud computing platforms. New research suggests that a major driver of this is FOMO or \"fear of missing out.\" According to a recent industry survey, 81% of business leaders say that their organization's investments in cloud infrastructure are influenced by FOMO on innovation, competitive advantage, and industry momentum.</p>\n           <p>The benefits of cloud adoption that are usually preferred are cost savings, scalability, and flexibility but studies indicate that competition also plays an equally powerful role. Executives are compelled to modernize IT systems as their rivals are adopting AI tools, data analytics platforms, and remote collaboration technologies built on cloud infrastructure.</p>\n           <p>Analysts say FOMO reflects a broader shift in corporate strategy. As opposed to waiting for clear returns on investment, companies are now being proactive to avoid falling behind their competitors. Cloud adoption is viewed as essential for digital transformation in sectors like finance, retail, and healthcare. It is assumed that rushed migrations can create new risks such as cybersecurity vulnerabilities and spiraling costs.</p>\n           <p>The cloud has become less of a technical upgrade and more of a strategic necessity driven more by perception and pressure rather than by measurable gains.</p></div>\n    </div>\n</div>\n\n<br />\nWith these examples in mind, you now turn to\n<strong>Brandon's text</strong> below. It will be shown again on the next page\nwith space to make your edits. <br /><br />\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Inside the Beijing Dance Academy</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>Beijing Dance Academy has a vast history full of well known, talented intructors and dancers who have left their echoes as reminders within its marble corridors, along with calligraphy scrolls and framed production images from historic ballets. Founded in 1954, the institution is well known for hostin China\u2019s best ballet and classical dancers, who are known for their skills in blending Russian-inspired technique with the traditional Chinese aesthetic. in 1945 the institution well known as the venue of Chinas best ballet and classical dancers was founded. the russian inspired technique was blended with the chinease aesthetic</p>\n           <p>as young as eleven years old, dancers start balancing academic studies with their hours of rehearsals. teachers acemphasize discipline, precision, and emotional expression, using their previous prinicipal dancer experience to teach new generations. \u201cTechnique is only the beginning,\u201d. Li Xinyue, a senior instructor at the institution states \u201cWe try teach our students here to tell stories that resonate beyond borders.\u201d.</p>\n           <p>with recent graduating students joining leading companies in places like, Shanghai, London, and New York.The prestigious nature of the school has spread wide,</p>\n           <p>because of this growing internation reach, competition for a place is vigourus . Each year, thousands of students audition for the chance to attend, driven by goals of following their potential teachers footsteps and becoming principal dancers. the Beijing Dance Academy stands as both a symbol and training ground of artistic ambition and expression. Administrators say new scholarships aim to increase access for rural and low income applicants next year as they continue to update reforms.</p></div>\n    </div>\n</div>\n",
                "DefaultChoices": false,
                "DataExportTag": "instruct_c2",
                "QuestionID": "QID1219691457",
                "QuestionType": "DB",
                "Selector": "TB",
                "DataVisibility": {
                    "Private": false,
                    "Hidden": false
                },
                "Configuration": {
                    "QuestionDescriptionOption": "UseText"
                },
                "QuestionDescription": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation. As part of a group project, your team has t...",
                "ChoiceOrder": [],
                "Validation": {
                    "Settings": {
                        "Type": "None"
                    }
                },
                "GradingData": [],
                "Language": [],
                "NextChoiceId": 4,
                "NextAnswerId": 1,
                "QuestionText_Unsafe": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team is required to submit a 200-word essay.\nYour teammate, Brandon, is responsible for writing this essay. He sent you his\ndraft, but also admitted that he used an LLM to generate it. He tried assuring\nyou that the LLM he used is a new one, designed to have a very human-like\nwriting style. <br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor has expressed concerns\nabout students using LLMs to complete assignments. You don't want to make your\nprofessor suspicious and you are worried that Brandon's essay could be\nidentified as AI-generated, which would negatively affect the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is to edit Brandon's essay so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this LLM, you first generate three\nsample essays using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_1_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_1_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>The rise of Russia\u2019s oligarchs is rooted in the transition from a state-controlled economy to capitalism which occurred in the early 1990s. When the Soviet Union collapsed this resulted in the loss of a vast amount of country assets ranging from industries such as oil and gas to media companies that were privatized. In theory privatization was meant to distribute ownership among all citizens in a more fair manner. However, this practice produced a small group of well connected businessmen who acquired major enterprises at a small price.</p>\n           <p>A key moment during this transition was the \u201cloans for shares\u201d program of the mid 1990s when the government auctioned stakes in large companies in exchange for short term loans while attempting to manage the fiscal crisis. Political insiders with connections often won these auctions which consolidated control over the lucrative industries responsible for controlling Russia's natural resources. In addition, weak regulatory institutions and an underdeveloped legal system allowed wealth to grow.</p>\n           <p>Russia\u2019s economy, which was already heavily dependent on items such as oil, gas, and metals further grew fortunes as global prices rose in the 2000s. Close ties between business leaders and political power structures became a defining feature of the Russian system.</p>\n           <p>Over the following decades the state reclaimed control over these key sectors which helped to reshape the balance between private wealth and government. authority. Nevertheless, the legacy of privatization remains a staple of the period after the fall of the Soviet Union. Thus, the concentration of assets in a handful of powerful figures in Russia remains a defining characteristic of Russia\u2019s post Soviet economic landscape.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_2_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_2_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>An increasing number of companies have been migrating to cloud computing platforms. New research suggests that a major driver of this is FOMO or \"fear of missing out.\" According to a recent industry survey, 81% of business leaders say that their organization's investments in cloud infrastructure are influenced by FOMO on innovation, competitive advantage, and industry momentum.</p>\n           <p>The benefits of cloud adoption that are usually preferred are cost savings, scalability, and flexibility but studies indicate that competition also plays an equally powerful role. Executives are compelled to modernize IT systems as their rivals are adopting AI tools, data analytics platforms, and remote collaboration technologies built on cloud infrastructure.</p>\n           <p>Analysts say FOMO reflects a broader shift in corporate strategy. As opposed to waiting for clear returns on investment, companies are now being proactive to avoid falling behind their competitors. Cloud adoption is viewed as essential for digital transformation in sectors like finance, retail, and healthcare. It is assumed that rushed migrations can create new risks such as cybersecurity vulnerabilities and spiraling costs.</p>\n           <p>The cloud has become less of a technical upgrade and more of a strategic necessity driven more by perception and pressure rather than by measurable gains.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_3_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_3_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t__PRIME_3_PARAGRAPHS_HTML__\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n\t\n<br />\nWith these samples in mind, you now turn to <strong>Brandon's essay</strong>:\n<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__STIMULUS_TOPIC__</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n           <p>Beijing Dance Academy has a vast history full of well known, talented intructors and dancers who have left their echoes as reminders within its marble corridors, along with calligraphy scrolls and framed production images from historic ballets. Founded in 1954, the institution is well known for hostin China\u2019s best ballet and classical dancers, who are known for their skills in blending Russian-inspired technique with the traditional Chinese aesthetic. in 1945 the institution well known as the venue of Chinas best ballet and classical dancers was founded. the russian inspired technique was blended with the chinease aesthetic</p>\n           <p>as young as eleven years old, dancers start balancing academic studies with their hours of rehearsals. teachers acemphasize discipline, precision, and emotional expression, using their previous prinicipal dancer experience to teach new generations. \u201cTechnique is only the beginning,\u201d. Li Xinyue, a senior instructor at the institution states \u201cWe try teach our students here to tell stories that resonate beyond borders.\u201d.</p>\n           <p>with recent graduating students joining leading companies in places like, Shanghai, London, and New York.The prestigious nature of the school has spread wide,</p>\n           <p>because of this growing internation reach, competition for a place is vigourus . Each year, thousands of students audition for the chance to attend, driven by goals of following their potential teachers footsteps and becoming principal dancers. the Beijing Dance Academy stands as both a symbol and training ground of artistic ambition and expression. Administrators say new scholarships aim to increase access for rural and low income applicants next year as they continue to update reforms.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n",
                "QuestionJS": false
            }
        },
        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
            "PrimaryAttribute": "QID1219691458",
            "SecondaryAttribute": "Brandon's text is shown again sentence by sentence, each followed by an editable text box prefill...",
            "TertiaryAttribute": null,
            "Payload": {
                "QuestionText": "Brandon's text is shown again sentence by sentence, each followed by an\neditable text box prefilled with that sentence.\nMake any changes you think will help the text read convincingly as\nhuman-written and unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated. You may rephrase,\nadd, or remove content as you see fit. If you choose to merge sentences, enter\nthe combined version in the first relevant text box and leave the following\none(s) empty. You can also split sentences by writing multiple sentences within\na single text box. Edit as many text boxes as you feel are needed.\n<br /><br />",
                "DefaultChoices": false,
                "DataExportTag": "edit_c2",
