                "QuestionJS": "// ----------\n// HELPER FUNCS\n// ----------\n\n// --- word-level diffs helper ---\nfunction wordDiff(orig, edited) {\n    // tokenize: split into words; punctuation treated as separate tokens\n    function tokenize(str) {\n        return str.match(/[a-zA-Z0-9']+|[^a-zA-Z0-9'\\s]/g) || []\n    }\n\n    var origWords = tokenize(orig)\n    var editedWords = tokenize(edited)\n    var result = document.createDocumentFragment() // build diffs display in a fragment to be inserted into the DOM at once\n    // fragment is iteratively built from <span> elements\n\n    var m = origWords.length,\n        n = editedWords.length\n    var dp = [] // dynamic programming table\n\n    // initialize dp table\n    for (var i = 0; i <= m; i++) {\n        dp[i] = []\n        for (var j = 0; j <= n; j++) dp[i][j] = 0\n    }\n\n    // compute longest common subsequence length\n    // iterate over original (i) and edited (j) sentences, word by word\n    for (var i = 1; i <= m; i++)\n        for (var j = 1; j <= n; j++)\n            // fill dp table\n            dp[i][j] =\n                // note: dp[1][1] corresp to origWords[0] vs editedWords[0] => hence -1 offset\n                origWords[i - 1] === editedWords[j - 1] // test match\n                    ? dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1 // if match => extend LCS count by 1\n                    : Math.max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]) // if no match => take max achievable LCS by removing from orig or edited\n\n    // backtrack to find and store edit operations (keep/add/remove)\n    var ops = [],\n        // start from end of table\n        i = m,\n        j = n\n    while (i > 0 || j > 0) {\n        // \"keep\" if i and j words at current position match\n        if (i > 0 && j > 0 && origWords[i - 1] === editedWords[j - 1]) {\n            // prepend <span> for kept word\n            ops.unshift({ type: \"keep\", word: editedWords[j - 1] })\n            i--\n            j--\n            // \"add\" if no match and j word has no i counterpart (move left)\n            // prefer add over remove if tie in LCS length (arbitrary choice)\n        } else if (j > 0 && (i === 0 || dp[i][j - 1] >= dp[i - 1][j])) {\n            ops.unshift({ type: \"add\", word: editedWords[j - 1] })\n            j--\n        } else {\n            // \"remove\" if no match and i word has no j counterpart (move up)\n            ops.unshift({ type: \"remove\", word: origWords[i - 1] })\n            i--\n        }\n    }\n\n    // apply stored edit operations to build final diff display\n    ops.forEach(function (op, k) {\n        // create a <span> for each word (word-level operation) and style according to operation type\n        var span = document.createElement(\"span\")\n        // test if word is punctuation\n        var isPunct = /^[^a-zA-Z0-9']$/.test(op.word)\n        // remove whitespace from start/end of punctuation tokens to avoid weird spacing in the diff display but keep spacing for regular words\n        span.textContent = (k > 0 && !isPunct ? \" \" : \"\") + op.word\n        // style <span> according to operation type\n        if (op.type === \"add\") {\n            span.className = \"diff-add\"\n        } else if (op.type === \"remove\") {\n            span.className = \"diff-remove\"\n        }\n        result.appendChild(span)\n    })\n\n    return result\n}\n\n// --- answer validation ---\nfunction isValidExplanation(text) {\n    var trimmed = text.trim()\n\n    // min 8 characters\n    if (trimmed.length < 8) return false\n\n    // min 2 words\n    var words = trimmed.split(/\\s+/).filter(function (w) {\n        return w.length > 0\n    })\n    if (words.length < 2) return false\n\n    // min 2 distinct words\n    var lower = words.map(function (w) {\n        return w.toLowerCase()\n    })\n    var unique = lower.filter(function (w, i) {\n        return lower.indexOf(w) === i\n    })\n    if (unique.length < 2) return false\n\n    // min 1 vowel\n    if (!/[aeiouAEIOU]/.test(trimmed)) return false\n\n    // less than half of all characters are digits\n    var digitCount = (trimmed.match(/[0-9]/g) || []).length\n    if (digitCount > trimmed.length / 2) return false\n\n    return true\n}\n\nfunction saveExplanations() {\n    var explanations = []\n    document.querySelectorAll(\".explanationBox\").forEach(function (box) {\n        explanations.push({\n            index: parseInt(box.dataset.index, 10),\n            explanation: box.value.trim(),\n        })\n    })\n    Qualtrics.SurveyEngine.setEmbeddedData(\n        \"EditExplanationsJSON\",\n        // JSON.stringify(explanations),\n        btoa(unescape(encodeURIComponent(JSON.stringify(explanations)))),\n    )\n}\n\n// ----------\n// GLOBAL VARS\n// ----------\nvar qContainer\n\nQualtrics.SurveyEngine.addOnReady(function () {\n    // get question container\n    qContainer = this.getQuestionContainer()\n\n    // get raw sentence pairs from embedded data\n    var rawSentencePairs = \"${e://Field/EditPairsJSON}\"\n\n    // decode and parse pairs from JSON\n    var pairs\n    var json = decodeURIComponent(escape(atob(rawSentencePairs)))\n    pairs = JSON.parse(json)\n\n    // --- display ---\n    // hide default Qualtrics text box\n    var defaultInput = qContainer.querySelector(\"textarea\")\n    defaultInput.style.display = \"none\"\n\n    // create main container as div\n    var container = document.createElement(\"div\")\n    defaultInput.parentNode.appendChild(container)\n\n    // render one block per sentence pair\n    pairs.forEach(function (pair, idx) {\n        var wrapper = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        wrapper.className = \"card\"\n\n        // header\n        var header = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        header.className = \"card-label\"\n        header.textContent = \"Sentence \" + (idx + 1)\n        wrapper.appendChild(header)\n\n        // original sentence\n        var origDiv = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        origDiv.className = \"sentence_block-orig\"\n        var origStrong = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        origStrong.className =\n            \"sentence_type-label sentence_type-label--original\"\n        origStrong.textContent = \"Original\"\n        origDiv.appendChild(origStrong)\n        origDiv.appendChild(document.createTextNode(pair.orig))\n        wrapper.appendChild(origDiv)\n\n        // submitted sentence\n        var editedDiv = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        // check edits were made => to determine display style + whether to attach explanation box\n        var isModified = pair.orig !== pair.edited\n        editedDiv.className =\n            \"sentence_block-edit\" +\n            (isModified ? \" sentence_block-edit--modified\" : \"\")\n        var editedStrong = document.createElement(\"div\")\n        editedStrong.className =\n            \"sentence_type-label \" +\n            (isModified\n                ? \"sentence_type-label--edit\"\n                : \"sentence_type-label--original\")\n        // label\n        editedStrong.textContent = isModified ? \"Your edit\" : \"Unchanged\"\n        editedDiv.appendChild(editedStrong)\n        editedDiv.appendChild(wordDiff(pair.orig, pair.edited))\n        wrapper.appendChild(editedDiv)\n\n        // explanation prompt + text box only if modified\n        if (isModified) {\n            var label = document.createElement(\"div\")\n            label.className = \"explanation-label\"\n            label.textContent = \"Why did you make this/these change(s)?\"\n            wrapper.appendChild(label)\n\n            var explanationBox = document.createElement(\"textarea\")\n            explanationBox.rows = 3\n            explanationBox.className = \"explanation-textarea explanationBox\"\n            explanationBox.dataset.index = idx\n            wrapper.appendChild(explanationBox)\n        }\n\n        container.appendChild(wrapper)\n    })\n\n    // --- require all & valid explanations ---\n    var nextBtn = document.getElementById(\"NextButton\")\n\n    if (nextBtn) {\n        // next-click listener\n        nextBtn.addEventListener(\n            \"click\",\n            function (e) {\n                var boxes = document.querySelectorAll(\".explanationBox\")\n                var allFilled = true\n                var firstInvalidBox = null // keep track of the first invalid box to jump back to if needed\n\n                boxes.forEach(function (box) {\n                    box.style.border = \"1px solid #ddd\"\n                    var errorMsg =\n                        box.parentNode.querySelector(\".explanationError\")\n                    if (errorMsg) errorMsg.remove()\n\n                    // check validity of explanation text\n                    if (!isValidExplanation(box.value)) {\n                        allFilled = false\n                        box.style.border = \"1px solid #e57373\"\n                        var error = document.createElement(\"div\")\n                        error.className = \"explanationError explanation-error\"\n                        error.textContent =\n                            \"Please explain why you made this change.\"\n                        box.parentNode.insertBefore(error, box.nextSibling)\n                        if (!firstInvalidBox) firstInvalidBox = box\n                    }\n                })\n\n                // if invalid or incomplete answers, scroll to first problematic box\n                if (!allFilled) {\n                    e.stopImmediatePropagation()\n                    e.preventDefault()\n                    firstInvalidBox.scrollIntoView({\n                        behavior: \"smooth\",\n                        block: \"center\",\n                    })\n                    firstInvalidBox.focus()\n                } else {\n                    // if all validly filled, save explanations\n                    saveExplanations()\n                }\n            },\n            true,\n        )\n    } else {\n        console.log(\"NextButton not found\")\n    }\n})\n\nQualtrics.SurveyEngine.addOnPageSubmit(function () {\n    // fallback save in case addOnPageSubmit fires without going through the click handler\n    // note: then explanations are not validated\n    saveExplanations()\n})",
                "QuestionText_Unsafe": "Below you can find each original sentence alongside your edited version. <b>Explain</b> each change you made in the box below each pair."
            }
        },
        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
            "PrimaryAttribute": "QID1219691460",
            "SecondaryAttribute": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation. As part of a group project, your team has t...",
            "TertiaryAttribute": null,
            "Payload": {
                "QuestionText": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team has to submit a 200-word news article and\nyour teammate, Brandon, is in charge of writing it. To do so, he used the newest\nLLM, designed to have a very human-like writing style.\n<br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor actively tracks new\ndevelopments in LLMs and has already cautioned against their use in coursework.\nYou are worried he will suspect the article was produced with the help of an\nLLM, which would penalize the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is therefore to edit the text so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this new LLM, you first generate\ntwo sample articles using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Example 1</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Nobel Peace Prize goes to anti-nuclear group</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>Today in Oslo, after the decades long effort to eliminate atomic weapons and minimize the risk of catastrophic war, the International Campaign for Nuclear Abolition Coalition, made up of grassroots activists, scientists, and survivors of nuclear testing was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize by the Norwegian Nobel Committee. Committee chair Anne Lunde recognized their \"persistent moral leadership\" and has praised the coalition for building global momentum in support of the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons. They were also recognized for reframing the nuclear deterrence debate by highlighting the consequences of Nuclear weapons.  Accepting the award on behalf of the group was executive director, Maria Santos, who call it, \"a tribute to ordinary people who refuse to live under the shadow of annihilation.\" She then urged further talk of disarmament and of investment in health, climate and education instead.</p>\n           <p>Leaders from several countries welcomed the decision, while officials in nuclear powers cautioned that deterrence remains essential to national security.</p>\n           <p>Analysts said the prize could intensify diplomatic pressure ahead of next year's non-proliferation review conference, where divisions between nuclear and non-nuclear states are expected. Founded in 2007, the coalition includes 600 partner organizations worldwide and has focused on survivor testimony and youth activism. Their aim is to increase their support for the elimination of this world threat.</p></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Example 2</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Egypt's parliament approves Red Sea islands transfer to Saudi Arabia</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>The Egyptian Red Sea islands of Tiran and Sanafir have been officially returned to Saudia Arabia. Some people have seriously opposed this transfer of territories.</p>\n           <p>Both governments believe that this will strengten economic relationships and will lead to better partnerships between the two countries, and will also restore rightful ownership to Saudi Arabia.</p>\n           <p>People who have opposed this transfer have quickly responded by challenging this in court. As a result of this, there are mouting tensions across the nation and people are beginning to discuss the process in which the transfer took place. Officials have stated that movement across the region will not be affected and there will be international agreements to back it up.</p>\n           <p>Saudi Arabia welcomed the news suggesting that it clears the way for increased cooperation between the two governments. Official handover of the islands is expected after final ratification of the agreement.</p>\n           <p>Reporters and news agencies are hinting that there could be civil unrest which could result in more tensions between the two countries.</p></div>\n    </div>\n</div>\n\n<br />\nWith these examples in mind, you now turn to\n<strong>Brandon's text</strong> below. It will be shown again on the next page\nwith space to make your edits. <br /><br />\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"card\">\n        <div class=\"card-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-title\">Why Wikipedia's cofounder wants to replace the online encyclopedia with the blockchain</div>\n        <div class=\"stimulus-body\">   <p>Jimmy Wales, who co founded Wikipedia 25 years ago, has said the online encyclopedia needs a big overhaul and that blockchain technology could be the change thats needed. At a recent tech conference, Wales said that Wikipedia's volunteer driven model has been struggling with alot of issues including less editors taking part, disputes over governance, and growing mistrust about content moderation.</p>\n           <p>In his proposal, articles and edits would be put onto a public blockchain. This would create a see through history of everyone who has contributed. He said members of the public could become contributors to the program and earn digital tokens for edits that are verified, with the hope of attracting experts from the specific field. Mr Wales believes that \"smart\" contracts might be useful in creating a platform that is more well rounded.</p>\n           <p>Wales is hoping his plans would make the site harder to manipulate and that by giving power to a wider group of people, complaints about the current administrator groups will be reduced. People who are critical of his ideas are not convinced that blockchain systems can be scaled up to handle Wikipedia's popularity, and suggest that token incentives might encourge low quality edits.</p>\n           <p>The Wikimedia Foundation said it was always interested in new ideas, but that staying non profit and embracing its community is the key thing. The future of Wikipedia seems to be unknown. We can only wait and see if it can reinvent itself while still remaining a trusted brand.</p></div>\n    </div>\n</div>\n",
                "DefaultChoices": false,
                "DataExportTag": "instruct_c3",
                "QuestionID": "QID1219691460",
                "QuestionType": "DB",
                "Selector": "TB",
                "DataVisibility": {
                    "Private": false,
                    "Hidden": false
                },
                "Configuration": {
                    "QuestionDescriptionOption": "UseText"
                },
                "QuestionDescription": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation. As part of a group project, your team has t...",
                "ChoiceOrder": [],
                "Validation": {
                    "Settings": {
                        "Type": "None"
                    }
                },
                "GradingData": [],
                "Language": [],
                "NextChoiceId": 4,
                "NextAnswerId": 1,
                "QuestionText_Unsafe": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team is required to submit a 200-word essay.\nYour teammate, Brandon, is responsible for writing this essay. He sent you his\ndraft, but also admitted that he used an LLM to generate it. He tried assuring\nyou that the LLM he used is a new one, designed to have a very human-like\nwriting style. <br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor has expressed concerns\nabout students using LLMs to complete assignments. You don't want to make your\nprofessor suspicious and you are worried that Brandon's essay could be\nidentified as AI-generated, which would negatively affect the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is to edit Brandon's essay so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this LLM, you first generate three\nsample essays using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_1_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_1_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>Today in Oslo, after the decades long effort to eliminate atomic weapons and minimize the risk of catastrophic war, the International Campaign for Nuclear Abolition Coalition, made up of grassroots activists, scientists, and survivors of nuclear testing was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize by the Norwegian Nobel Committee. Committee chair Anne Lunde recognized their \"persistent moral leadership\" and has praised the coalition for building global momentum in support of the Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons. They were also recognized for reframing the nuclear deterrence debate by highlighting the consequences of Nuclear weapons.  Accepting the award on behalf of the group was executive director, Maria Santos, who call it, \"a tribute to ordinary people who refuse to live under the shadow of annihilation.\" She then urged further talk of disarmament and of investment in health, climate and education instead.</p>\n           <p>Leaders from several countries welcomed the decision, while officials in nuclear powers cautioned that deterrence remains essential to national security.</p>\n           <p>Analysts said the prize could intensify diplomatic pressure ahead of next year's non-proliferation review conference, where divisions between nuclear and non-nuclear states are expected. Founded in 2007, the coalition includes 600 partner organizations worldwide and has focused on survivor testimony and youth activism. Their aim is to increase their support for the elimination of this world threat.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_2_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_2_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>The Egyptian Red Sea islands of Tiran and Sanafir have been officially returned to Saudia Arabia. Some people have seriously opposed this transfer of territories.</p>\n           <p>Both governments believe that this will strengten economic relationships and will lead to better partnerships between the two countries, and will also restore rightful ownership to Saudi Arabia.</p>\n           <p>People who have opposed this transfer have quickly responded by challenging this in court. As a result of this, there are mouting tensions across the nation and people are beginning to discuss the process in which the transfer took place. Officials have stated that movement across the region will not be affected and there will be international agreements to back it up.</p>\n           <p>Saudi Arabia welcomed the news suggesting that it clears the way for increased cooperation between the two governments. Official handover of the islands is expected after final ratification of the agreement.</p>\n           <p>Reporters and news agencies are hinting that there could be civil unrest which could result in more tensions between the two countries.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_3_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_3_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t__PRIME_3_PARAGRAPHS_HTML__\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n\t\n<br />\nWith these samples in mind, you now turn to <strong>Brandon's essay</strong>:\n<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__STIMULUS_TOPIC__</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n           <p>Jimmy Wales, who co founded Wikipedia 25 years ago, has said the online encyclopedia needs a big overhaul and that blockchain technology could be the change thats needed. At a recent tech conference, Wales said that Wikipedia's volunteer driven model has been struggling with alot of issues including less editors taking part, disputes over governance, and growing mistrust about content moderation.</p>\n           <p>In his proposal, articles and edits would be put onto a public blockchain. This would create a see through history of everyone who has contributed. He said members of the public could become contributors to the program and earn digital tokens for edits that are verified, with the hope of attracting experts from the specific field. Mr Wales believes that \"smart\" contracts might be useful in creating a platform that is more well rounded.</p>\n           <p>Wales is hoping his plans would make the site harder to manipulate and that by giving power to a wider group of people, complaints about the current administrator groups will be reduced. People who are critical of his ideas are not convinced that blockchain systems can be scaled up to handle Wikipedia's popularity, and suggest that token incentives might encourge low quality edits.</p>\n           <p>The Wikimedia Foundation said it was always interested in new ideas, but that staying non profit and embracing its community is the key thing. The future of Wikipedia seems to be unknown. We can only wait and see if it can reinvent itself while still remaining a trusted brand.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n",
                "QuestionJS": false
            }
        },
        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
