                "NextChoiceId": 4,
                "NextAnswerId": 1,
                "QuestionText_Unsafe": "Imagine you find yourself in the following situation.<br /><br />\n\nAs part of a group project, your team is required to submit a 200-word essay.\nYour teammate, Brandon, is responsible for writing this essay. He sent you his\ndraft, but also admitted that he used an LLM to generate it. He tried assuring\nyou that the LLM he used is a new one, designed to have a very human-like\nwriting style. <br /><br />\n\nHowever, this puts your group at risk. Your professor has expressed concerns\nabout students using LLMs to complete assignments. You don't want to make your\nprofessor suspicious and you are worried that Brandon's essay could be\nidentified as AI-generated, which would negatively affect the entire group.\n<br /><br />\n\n<strong>Your task</strong> is to edit Brandon's essay so that it reads\nconvincingly as human-written and is unlikely to be identified as LLM-generated.\n<br /><br />\n\nTo get a better sense of the writing style of this LLM, you first generate three\nsample essays using it. They are shown below.<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_1_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_1_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>Dr. Amelia Hart, a renown quantum physicist, has been named Australian of the Year. Her pioneering research in quantum computing and her advocacy for science education is well documented over her career. The award was announced on Tuesday night. Specifically, it was her works in developing ultra stable qubits which would enable more practical use of quantum technologies.</p>\n           <p>Hart is a professor at the University of Sydney and director of the National Quantum Innovation Centre, Australia. Over the span of two decades, she has advanced methods which lower errors in quantum processors. Her team\u2019s breakthrough last year demonstrated a scalable architecture capable of working at room temperature. Experts say this is a milestone that could lower costs and expand commercial applications.</p>\n           <p>Hart has championed greater access to STEM education for girls and students in local communities beyond the laboratory. She has launched mentorship programs, advised government on critical technology policy, and spoken widely about the ethical implications of quantum breakthroughs.</p>\n           <p>Graciously she accepted the award in acknowledgement of her students and colleagues.  Her moment is significant in proving the power of science unity amongst nations.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_2_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_2_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t   <p>Jimmy Wales, who co founded Wikipedia 25 years ago, has said the online encyclopedia needs a big overhaul and that blockchain technology could be the change thats needed. At a recent tech conference, Wales said that Wikipedia's volunteer driven model has been struggling with alot of issues including less editors taking part, disputes over governance, and growing mistrust about content moderation.</p>\n           <p>In his proposal, articles and edits would be put onto a public blockchain. This would create a see through history of everyone who has contributed. He said members of the public could become contributors to the program and earn digital tokens for edits that are verified, with the hope of attracting experts from the specific field. Mr Wales believes that \"smart\" contracts might be useful in creating a platform that is more well rounded.</p>\n           <p>Wales is hoping his plans would make the site harder to manipulate and that by giving power to a wider group of people, complaints about the current administrator groups will be reduced. People who are critical of his ideas are not convinced that blockchain systems can be scaled up to handle Wikipedia's popularity, and suggest that token incentives might encourge low quality edits.</p>\n           <p>The Wikimedia Foundation said it was always interested in new ideas, but that staying non profit and embracing its community is the key thing. The future of Wikipedia seems to be unknown. We can only wait and see if it can reinvent itself while still remaining a trusted brand.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">__PRIME_3_LABEL__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__PRIME_3_TOPIC__</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n\t\t\t__PRIME_3_PARAGRAPHS_HTML__\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n\t\n<br />\nWith these samples in mind, you now turn to <strong>Brandon's essay</strong>:\n<br /><br />\n\n<div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-card\">\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-label\">Brandon's essay</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-title\">__STIMULUS_TOPIC__</div>\n\t<div class=\"stimulus-body\">\n           <p>Drones have shown promise to support and reduce the impact of global deforestation by offering lower cost and improved speed, compared to conventional methods. Drones are equipped with seed pods and artificial intelligence then take flight to help restore degraded landscapes. As well as analysing soil quality, the drones can release biodegradable seed capsules into the ground at remarkable speeds. Developed by environmental startups and university researchers, such as [company name], the drones are able to map barren terrain.</p>\n           <p>According to project leaders (relevant citation, date), a single drone can plant up to 40,000 trees per day, far surpassing traditional efforts. The devices use satellite imagery and machine learning to identify optimal planting sites. This offers benefits of increasing survival rates while reducing labour costs. The seed pods are also highly effective due to being packed with nutrients and natural pest deterrents. This gives saplings a better chance of growth.</p>\n           <p>Environmental advocates welcome the solution, (relevant citation, date) explains that the technology could prove crucial as wildfires, logging and agricultural expansion continue to shrink forests worldwide. Whilst being effective, critics have warned that drones are not fully advantageous and must complement broader conservation policies and community involvement. Field trials conducted in Brazil and Indonesia have shown promising early results, with thousands of native seedlings already sprouting. For example, in Brazil [Relevant data given]. With governments seeking scalable climate solutions worldwide, the outcome of the project is crucial for future forestry protection. Project developers and stakeholders hope expanded deployments over the next year will help reclaim vast stretches of lost forest and mitigate the impacts of climate change on forestry.</p>\n\t\t</div>\n\t</div>\n</div>\n",
                "QuestionJS": false
            }
        },
        {
            "SurveyID": "SV_cwM3MQomjAv0nJA",
            "Element": "SQ",
